# **Cloud Concepts**

- Cloud Computing is the practice of using network of remote servers hosted on the internet to store, manage and process data instead of a local sever or pc OR the delivery of computing services over the internet by using a pay-as-you-go pricing model. You typically pay only for the cloud services you use  
- Cloud Providers basic services are: compute power (processing volume) & storage (volume of data like hard drive)  
- Evolution of computing: Dedicated server → Virtual Machines (VM) → Containers (software name \- docker deamon) → Functions (managed VMs running managed containers, also known as serverless compute. The most cost-effective)  
- Dedicated server: one physical machine for a single business, Virtual Private Server (VPS): one physical machine for a single business virtualized into sub-machine, Shared hosting: one physical machine shared by hundred of businesses, Cloud Hosting: Multiple physical machine that act as one system, broken down into multiple cloud services  
- Common Cloud Services for IaaS (Compute, Storage, Networking, Databases)  
- Azure: Microsft Cloud Provider Service  
- Benefits: PAYG, Go global, Secure by default, Reliability, Scalability, Elasticity, Current (always upgraded)  
- Types of Cloud Computing: SaaS (for customers, scenarios: Email & Messaging, Business Productivity Applications, Finance & Expense Tracking), PaaS (for developers, scenarios: Development framework, Analytics/business intelligence), IaaS ( for admins, scenarios: Lift-and-Shift Migration, Testing & Development)  
- Cloud Computing Responsibilities: ***IaaS places the most responsibility on the consumer,*** with the cloud provider being responsible for the basics of physical security, power, and connectivity. On the other end of the spectrum, SaaS places most of the responsibility with the cloud provider. ***PaaS*** (Azure Storage accounts and Azure App Service), being a middle ground between IaaS and ***SaaS (MS 365\) can automatically scale without any manual intervention,*** rests somewhere in the middle and evenly distributes responsibility between the cloud provider and the consumer.

## **Benefits of Cloud**

- Availability (Uptime): Means that cloud-based apps can provide a continuous user experience with no apparent downtime, even when things go wrong. Azure load balancer allows to evenly distribute traffic to multiple servers in one or more datacenter. Different services have different SLAs, sometimes different tiers of the same service will offer different SLAs, which can increase or decrease the promised availability.  
- Agility means that you can deploy and configure cloud-based resources quickly as app requirements change.  
- Scalability: Vertical scaling (scaling up) is focused on increasing or decreasing the capabilities of resources e.g., adding more memory (CPU/RAM) to one server while horizontal severe (scaling out) is adding or subtracting the number of resources.e.g, adding more servers, VMs, containers  
- Elasticity: Autoscaling. Increase or decrease capacity based on demand, traffic, or computing power. Mostly associated with horizontal scaling as vertical scaling is difficult for traditional architecture. Azure VM scale sets or SQL severe stretch database are tools used.  
- Reliability: Ability of a system to recover from failures and continue to function. It's also one of the pillars of the Microsoft Azure Well-Architected Framework.  
- Predictability: Performance predictability (Autoscaling, load balancing, and high availability) or cost predictability (predicting or forecasting the cost of the cloud spend using TCO).   
- Fault tolerance: no singlepoint of failure by using failovers (shift traffic to a redundant/secondary system in case the primary system fails) e.g., ***Azure Traffic Manager (DNS based traffic balancer)***  
- Durability: Recover from disaster & prevent loss of data.

## **Cost Management**

- TCO (***Understand & compare*** cost savings of operating solution on Azure compared to on-premises), Pricing Calculator (***Determine & Estimate Azure services*** that fit budget), Azure Advisor (Monitor actual costs, Recommendation & Optimization) are tools to helps understand costs & savings when moving to the cloud  
- Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) \- 75% when you move from on-premises to azure  
- Cost Management: Cost Alerts (Budget alerts, Credits alerts (Works for Enterprise Agreement), Department spending quota alerts (Works for Enterprise Agreement (EA), can be configured in EA portal) AND Budgets  
- Tags are used to organize related resources & place them in their own subscriptions. It is useful for: Resource Management, Cost Management & Optimization, Operations Management, Security, Governance & Regulatory Compliance, Workload Optimization & Automation.   
- Azure Reservations can be used to minimize the costs of VMs without reducing the functionality of the VMs. You commit to a one-year or three-year term plan. However, you have the option to pay your Azure reservations monthly instead of an upfront payment, allowing you to spread out the cost.  
- Cloud computing operates on a consumption-based model (OpEx). OpEx costs depends on Resource type, Consumption, Maintenance, Geography, Subscription type, Azure Marketplace  
- Capital expenditure (CapEx) \- physical infrastructure costs, Operational Expenditure (OpEx) \- non-physical costs

### **Azure Resource Manager (ARM)**

- ARM is a service that allows you to manage Azure resources  
- It is a collection of service that makes up management layer that allows: Create, update, delete resources; Apply management feature, Writing IaC.  
- Features that make up ARM layer are: Subscriptions (grant access to Azure services based on billing & support agreement), Management Groups (logical grouping of multiple subscriptions), Resource Groups (logical grouping of multiple resources in a subscription), Resource Providers, Azure Blueprints, Resource Tags, Acces Control (IAM), RBAC, Azure Policies, & ARM Templates  
- Gatekeeper that allows flow of requests and decides whether the request can be performed on a resource  
- Scoping: Boundary of control for Azure resources and a way of governing by logical grouping & applying restrictions  
- Bicep is a language that uses declarative syntax to deploy Azure resources. A Bicep file defines the infrastructure and configuration. Then, ARM deploys that environment based on your Bicep file. While similar to an ARM template, which is written in JSON, Bicep files tend to use a simpler, more concise style.  
- Azure IaC examples: ARM Templates, Bicep, Terraform  
- ARM Templates: IaC. Process of managing and provisioning computer data centers (e.g, Azure) through machine-readable definition files (e.g. JSON files) rather than physical hardware configuration or interactive configuration tools. ***It can be declarative or imperative***. They are ***JSON files*** that define Azure resources that you want to provision & Azure services that you want to configure. They can be ***exported.***

# **Azure Architecture & Services**

## **Architectural Components**

- Physical Infrastucture are Datacenters while Management Infrastucture includes Azure resources and resource groups, subscriptions, and accounts.  
- Resources → Resource Group → Subscription → Management Groups  
- Subscriptions are unit of management, billing and scale. Subscription boundaries are: Billing Boundary & Access Control Boundary. They can further be separated into: Environment, Organizational structures, Billing  
- Management Group: manage access, policies, and compliance for subscriptions  
- AZs: Physically separate datacenters within an Azure region. One or more datacenters. Combination of fault domain (logical grouping of hardware to avoid single point of failure within an AZ) and update domain (ensure resources don’t go offline). Set up with isolated boundary.   
- Azure services that support AZs fall into three categories: Zonal services, Zone-redundant services & Non-regional services:Datacenter: Building that contains hundreds of thousands of computers.   
- Region: Grouping of multiple datacenters or AZs, mostly 3 AZs close enough to provide low latency. Specialized regions are for compliance/legal reasons  
- Region Pair: When Azure regions appeared with another region within the same geography at least 300 miles away, this allows for the replication of resources across a geography to reduce events like natural disasters, civil unrest, power outages etc. E.g: West US paired with East US, South-East Asia paired with East Asia. Some azure services rely on paired regions for disaster recovery  
   ![][image12]  
- Sovereign Regions: Isolated from the main instance of Azure, may be used for compliance or legal purposes. Examples: US DoD Central, US Gov Virginia, US Gov Iowa, China East, China North  
- Geography: Market of 2/more regions that preserves data residency and compliance boundaries; US, Canada, Brazil, Mexico Azure govt (US). Not all services are available in all regions. 58 regions, 140 countries.   
- A zone is a geographical grouping of Azure regions for billing purposes.  
- Azure cloud services are categorized into three: 

![][image13]

- Availability set is logical grouping used in Azure to ensure VMs placed in the availability set are different fault/update domain to avoid downtime. Each VM in Availability set are assigned fault domain & update domain  
- Container Instances: docker as a service, stateless by default  
- Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS): Kubernetes as a service, containerized apps  
- Azure Service fabric: Tier-1 Enterprise containers as a service  
- Azure Functions: Event-driven, serverless compute. Runs code without the need of provisioning and managing a server.  
- Azure Batch: Plan, schedules & execute batch computer workloads across running 100+ jobs in parallel. It uses spot VMs to save money

## **VMs**

- VMs are the most common type of compute, IaaS, highly configurable server (choose storage disks/compute, size/memory, storage). 20 VMs per region, ***billed per second***. N.B: Azure doesn’t support VHDX format, only fixed VHD  
- Azure VM scale sets helps automatically increase or decrease VM capacity  
- VM can be grouped into: Update Domain, Fault Domain  
- Load balancer (e,g., application gateway for HTTP/HTTPS and Azure load balancer for TCP/UDP) can be associated with sacle sets coz it distribute VMs cross multiple AZ and allow for more robust health checks. Public Load Balancers are used to load balance Internet traffic to your VMs.   
- Scaling policy determine when VM should be added/removed (scale in/out) to meet capacity requirements. **Scale-in policy** (default, newest VM, oldest VM) determines what VM is removed (d) to decrease the capacity of the Scale Set while **update policy** (automatic, default, rolling) determine how VM instances are brought up-to-date with the latest scale set model  
- Health monitoring determine if server is healthy or unhealthy. Modes are application health extension (ping) & load balancer probe (needs to have a load balancer attached to the VM). Automatic repair policy is advised to be turned on  
- **Azure Virtual Deskto**p is a desktop & app virtualization service that runs on the cloud. Enables ***secure & remote work*** on any device, reduce cost of licensing & infrastructure, protect against outages, keep application & user data **secure using MS Entra ID, RBAC, MFA**. It is the only Windows client-based operating system that enables multiple concurrent users on a single VM

If you need to completely control the environment then you should choose a VM, Otherwise, container would be the better choice because of the portability, performance characteristics and management capabilities

### **Virtual Networking** 

- Network Interface is a Software or hardware interface between two pieces of equipment or protocol layers in a computer network while Network Interface Controller (NIC) is ​​a computer hardware component that connects a computer to a computer network. Also known as: network interface card, network adapter, LAN adapter, physical network interface   
- Azure Network Interfaces are attached to Azure VM instance. Without an NIC, An Azure VM instance would have no way to communicate. An Azure VM instance has to have an NIC and can have multiple NICs.  
- Subnets: Logical division of access space. It needs route table & Network Security Group (NSG). Types are Public & Private (private has to be configured by enabling Internet Getway (IG))   
- DNS is responsible for translating service name to IP address while Azure DNS is used for hosting service for DNS domain that provides name resolution by using Microsoft Azure infrastructure. You can’t use Azure DNS to buy domain name   
- VPN allows send & receive data across shared or public network. **Point-to-site VPN** connections are for individual networks to virtual networks and/or from a computer outside your organization back into your corporate network  (e.g., the client computer initiates an encrypted VPN connection to connect to the Azure virtual network). **Site-to-site VPN** link your **on-premises VPN device or gateway to the Azure VPN gateway in a virtual network,** VPN connection, works over IPSec and connects on-premises to Azure virtual network. Requires VPN device located on-premises, Works over public internet. In effect, the devices in Azure can appear as being on the local network. The connection is encrypted and works over the internet. **Network-to-network VPN** connect virtual network to other virtual networks   
- Policy-based VPN gateways specify statically the IP address of packets that should be encrypted through each tunnel. This type of device evaluates every data packet against those sets of IP addresses to choose the tunnel where that packet is going to be sent through.  
- **In Route-based gateways**, IPSec tunnels are modeled as a network interface or virtual tunnel interface. IP routing (either static routes or dynamic routing protocols) decides which one of these tunnel interfaces to use when sending each packet. Route-based VPNs are the preferred connection method for on-premises devices. They're more resilient to topology changes such as the creation of new subnets. ***Use a route-based VPN gateway for: Connections between virtual networks, Point-to-site connections, Multisite connections, Coexistence with an Azure ExpressRoute gateway***  
- **Azure Express Route** creates private connection (not over internet) between Azure datacenters & infrastructure on your ***premises*** or in a colocation environment to MS Office, Dynamic 365 & Azure Compute, Cloud services. Not a VPN connection but connect on-premises to Azure network through connectivity provider. Doesn’t pass through public internet. Connectivity can be from an: **any-to-any (IP VPN) network, a point-to-point Ethernet network, CloudExchange colocation, Directly from ExpressRoute sites. Benefits of ExpressRoute are: Global Connectivity, Dynamic Routing via Border Gateway Protocol, Built-in redundancy in every peering location**  
- ***ExpressRoute connections and Azure VPN Gateway are two services that you can use to connect an on-premises network to Azure.***   
- Service endpoints are used to expose Azure services to a virtual network, providing communication between the two. Works for only azure services. Provides secure and direct connectivity to Azure services over an optimized route over the Azure backbone network. Endpoints allow you to secure your critical Azure service resources to only your virtual networks.   
- Network Security Group (NSGs) allow you to configure inbound and outbound rules for virtual networks and virtual machines.   
- Azure Private Links allows you to establish secure connections between Azure resources so traffic remains within the Azure Network. Private Link Endpoint & Private Link Service

- Network security groups (can contain multiple inbound and outbound security rules) and network virtual appliances (specialized VMs that can be compared to a hardened network appliance) are used to filter network traffic between subnets. Subnet and Network interface can be attached to NSGs

### **Replication & Data Redundancy**

- Replication data redundancy is replication type of storage account that creates multiple copy of data to protect it. Types are: Primary Region redundancy, Secondary Region redundancy and Secondary Region redundancy with Read Access. The greater the level of redundancy, the more expensive the cost of replication.  
- Data are replicated 3 times in the primary region***.***   
- ***Options are:***   
  - ***Locally Redundant Storage (LRS)*** (which is cheapest option, 11 9s) replicates data 3 times within a single data center ***in Primary regions***   
  - ***Zone Redundant Storage (ZRS)*** (12 9s) replicates data across 3 AZs in ***Primary regions***   
  - ***Geo Redundant Storage*** (16 9s, copies data synchronously 3 times to primary region and asynchronously to a single region in secondary region) N:B: ***Replication to secondary regions in case of primary region disaster.***  
  - ***Geo-Zone-Redundant Storage*** (16 9s, copies data synchronously to 3 AZs in primary region and asynchronously to secondary region) N:B: ***Replication to secondary regions in case of primary region disaster***  
  - ***Read-access Geo Redundant Storage*** (16 9s, copies data synchronously to primary region and synchronously to secondary region). N:B: In this case,read access is enabledto the secondary region, your data is always available, even when the primary region is running optimally.   
  - ***Read-access Geo-Zone Redundant Storage*** (16 9s, copies data synchronously across 3 AZs in primary region and asynchronously to secondary region). N:B: In this case,read access is enabledto the secondary region, your data is always available, even when the primary region is running optimally.   
    

## **Data Migration**

### **Azure Migrate**

- Streamlined service for migration from an on-premises environment to the cloud, modernization and optimization on Azure  
- Easily integrates with third party tools form independent software vendors  
- It features tools like “Azure Migrate: Discover & Access” and “Migration and Modernization”  
- It offers unified migration platform, diverse tool set for migration and modernization   
- Assess, migrate and modernize in Azure migrate Hub  
- Databases, web apps, virtual desktop and data transfer   
- Integrated tools are ***“Azure Migrate: Discover & Access”, “Azure Migrate: Server Migration”, “Azure Database Migration Service”, “Data Migration Assistant”, “Azure AppService Migration Assistant”, “Azure Databox” and “Migration and Modernization”***

### **Azure Databox**

- Physical device. Inexpensive way of sending terabytes (80TB) of data in and out of Azure  
- Use cases are: Importing data (One time migrations, initial bulk transfers, periodic uploads) and Exporting data (Disaster recovery, security requirements and migration)

## **Azure identity, access, and security**

### **Microsoft Entra ID (Formerly Azure Active Directory (Azure AD))**

- Cloud-based Identity and Access Management (IAM) service used to manage users, sign-ins and access  
- Provides security tokens that you can use for the authentication flow of your cloud-based applications  
- Can be used to implement ***single sign-ons & authentication***  
- Editions are: free, Office 365 apps, Premium 1, Premium 2  
- Cannot create custom access control with Free and Office 365 apps edition   
- Use cases are: Authorize & authenticate to multiple sources to on-premises AD, web app, to Office 365 or Azure Microsoft   
- Domain is an area of network organized by single authentication DB. Entra ID domain is a logical grouping of Entra ID objects on a network  
- Domain Controller is a server that authenticate user identities & authorizes their access to resources  
- Domain Computer is a computer registered with a central authentication DB. It would be an Entra ID object  
- Entra ID Object is a basic element of Entra ID e.g., Users, Groups, Printers, Computers & Shared Folders  
- Group Policy Object is a virtual collection of policy settings. It contains what Entra ID objects has access to  
- Organization Units is a subdivision within Entra ID into which you can place objects like users, groups etc  
- Directory Service (e.g Entra ID Domain Services) provides the methods for storing directory data & making the data available to network users & administrators. It runs on a Domain Controller  
- ***Microsoft Entra ID Domain Services*** provides managed domain services like domain joins, group policies, Lightweight directory access protocol (LDAP) & Kerberos/NLTM authentication. You get the benefit of domain services without the need to deploy, manage, and patch domain controllers (DCs) in the cloud.  
- ***Microsoft Defender for Identity: Monitor the domain controller traffic and detect security threats using a sensor***

### **Single Sign-on (SSO)**

- A feature that allows user to authenticate once with Entra ID & then access multiple applications & services without having to authenticate again. Entra ID creates a security token that can be used to access other resources within the same organization.   
- SSO supports cloud-based applications, uses (Microsoft 365, Salesforce & Dropbox), on-premises applications (SharePoint & SAP) and custom-built applications (SAML, OpenID Connect & OAuth).   
- Choosing SSO depends on how the app is configured for authentication.   
- Cloud-based applications can use SAML, OpenID Connect, OAuth, password-based or linked for SSO which can also be disabled while on-premises applications can use password-based, Integrated Windows Authentication, header-based or linked for SSO. On-premises choices only work when apps are configured for Application Proxy  
- SSO Protocols supported in Azure are: OpenID Connect & OAuth (authentication & authorization of users in a secure & standardized manner), SAML (authentication & authorization data between an identity provide & a service provider), password-based authentication, Linked authentication, Integrated Windows authentication, Header based authentication (token)

### **External Identities (Microsoft Entra External ID)**

- Allow people outside your organization to access your apps & resources while letting them sign in using any identity they prefer  
- Capabilities are: Business-to-business collaboration, B2B Direct Connect, Microsoft Azure Active Directory business to customer (B2C)  
- ***May be similar to SSO***

### **Conditional Access**

- Tool that Microsoft Entra ID uses to allow (or deny) access to resources based on identity signals. Granular MFA access. Can vary the credentials needed to log in based on signals  
- Provides an extra player of security before allowing authenticated users access data or other assets by collecting signals from the user, makes decisions based on those signals, and then enforces that decision by allowing or denying the access request or challenging for a multifactor authentication response.

![][image21]

- Usually implemented via Conditional Access policies which are sets of rules that specify the conditions under which sign-ins are evaluated and allowed   
- Conditional Access policy enables MFA enforcement based on group membership   
- Conditional Access policiies analyzes signals (metadata associated with identity e.g., User/group membership, IP location, Device, Application, Real-time sign-in risk detection, Cloud apps, user risk) and verifies every attempt via access Controls  
- Use Cases: ***Require MFA***, Require access to services only through approved client applications, Require users to access your application ***only from managed devices***, Block access for untrusted sources or unknown locations 

### **Common Decisions**

- Defines the access controls that decide what level of access based on signal info.   
- Decisions are: block access, grant access  
- Can be used with MS 365 Business Premium, MS 365 E3 & E5, Entra ID P1 & P2

### **Active Directory Vs Microsoft Entra ID** 

- ### Active Directory manages multiple **on-premises** infrastructure components and systems using a single identity per user while MS Entra ID takes this approach to next level by providing organizations with an Identity as a Service (IDaaS) solutions for all apps across **cloud** & on-premises

**Passwordless Authentication**

- E.g: Windows Hello for Business (tied to user’s PC), Microsoft Authenticator app (employee’s phone), Fast Identity Online (FIDO2) security keys (an external security key or a platform key built into a device, are typically USB devices, but could also use Bluetooth or NFC)

### **Role Based Access Controls (RBAC)** 

- Azure RBAC helps ***manage who has access to Azure resources***, what they can do with the resources & area they have access to   
- Role assignments control access to resources and consists of ***security principal*** (identity requesting access to Azure resource, can be a user, group, or service principal, managed identity), ***role definition*** (collection of permissions. It lists the operations that can be performed such as read, write or delete. It can be high-level e.g., owner or specific e.g., virtual machine reader) and ***scope*** (set of resources that access for role assignments applies to. It access controls at the ***management, subscription, single resource or resource group level***)  
- Azure RBAC is enforced on any action that's initiated against an Azure resource that passes through Azure Resource Manager.   
- Azure RBAC doesn't enforce access permissions at the application or data level.   
- Four fundamental Azure roles (owner, contributor, reader and User Access Administrator) & 70 built in roles

### **Microsoft defender for cloud**

- Microsoft defender for cloud provides advanced protection for your Azure & on.-premises workloads by monitoring your cloud, on-premises, hybrid, and multicloud environments to provide guidance and notifications aimed at strengthening your security posture.  
- ***When necessary, Defender for Cloud can automatically deploy a Log Analytics agent to gather security-related data. For Azure machines, deployment is handled directly. For hybrid and multicloud environments, Microsoft Defender plans are extended to non-Azure machines with the help of Azure Arc. Cloud security posture management (CSPM) features are extended to multicloud machines without the need for any agents.***  
- Defender for Cloud helps detect threats across: Azure PaaS services, Azure Data Services, Networks. It can also defend hybrid resources, resources on other clouds. Use just-in-time ***(JIT) VM*** access  
- Defender for Cloud fills three vital needs as you manage the security of your resources and workloads in the cloud and on-premises: ***Continuously assess*** (Know your security posture. Identify and track vulnerabilities), ***Secure*** (Harden resources and services with Azure Security Benchmark), ***Defend*** (Detect and resolve threats to resources, workloads, and services)  
- Coverage allows to see resources types in subscription & eligible for protection by azure Defender  
- **Defend**: Security alerts describe details of affected resources, suggested remediation steps, and in some cases an option to trigger a logic app in response  
- Insights is rolling pane of news that give suggested reading, and high priority alerts gives Security Center's insights into pressing security matters that are relevant to you and your subscription

![][image22]

![][image23]

- Network map provides a graphical view with security overlays giving recommendations & insights for hardening network resources  
- Hybrid Cloud Protection: Azure Defender can protect VM in other cloud providers like AWS & Google Cloud Platform (GCP) via Azure Arc  
- Azure Arc is a control pane that can manage compute resources (Servers, Kubernetes Clusters, Azure Data Services, SQL Server, VM Preview) across cloud providers, on-premises and at the edge. Arc lets you extend your Azure compliance and monitoring to your hybrid and multi-cloud configurations. Azure Arc simplifies governance and management by delivering a consistent multi-cloud and on-premises management platform.  
- Azure Security Center: Unified infrastructure management security system that strengthen security posture of data centers and provides advanced threat priotection across hybrid workloads in cloud   
- Key Vault: Safeguard cryptographic keys & other secrets used by cloud apps & services. Secrets management, key management, certificate management & Hardware Security Module (HSM) (Piece of hardware designed to store encryption keys, FIP 140-2 compliant for multi-tenant & FIP 140-3 compliant for single-tenant )  
- Azure Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) Protection: Types are Volumetric attacks, protocol attacks and application layer attacks (WAF as protection). Tiers are: DDoS Protection Basic, DDoS Protection Standard  
- ***Management Groups: Managing multiple subscriptions*** into a hierarchical structure
